    <text id="B0339T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Kennedy requests that Jackson assist one of their teachers in securing adequate
                    housing and help her in the collection of funds.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    New York Branch<lb/>Freedman's Union Commission<lb/>No. 30 Vesey
                    Street.<lb/>(Late National Freedman's Relief Association)
                    <name type="recipient">Mr. Thos. P. Jackson,<lb/><abbr
                            expan="Bureau of Refugees, Freedmen and Abandoned Lands">B.R.F.
                            &amp; A.L.</abbr><lb/>Staunton, <abbr expan="Virginia">Va.</abbr></name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1867-10-11"><abbr expan="October">Oct.</abbr> 11th 1867</date>
                        <name type="place">New York</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir:</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>As I am informed by <abbr expan="Reverend">Rev.</abbr> R. M. Manly that Miss M.S.
                    Rowell, one of our teachers has been sent to your station, I take the liberty of
                    writing to you on her behalf. We are very desirous that she shall be situated
                    comfortably. Will you help her to find a good boarding place? She is instructed
                    to collect enough to pay her board. Will you give her advice as to the most
                    efficient mode of securing the money?</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>With Kindest regards,<lb/>Yours truly</salute>
                    <signed>Crammond Kennedy<lb/><abbr expan="Corresponding Secretary">Cor.
                        Sec.</abbr></signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
